    "body": "<span class=\"solution-visible-txt\">All submissions for this problem are available.</span><p>Raju loves data structures. He has a special knack for problems related to trees. One day, he stumbled upon one such problem related to nodes &amp; edges of weighted trees. The problem asked him to find the total number of vertex triplets (i, j, k) on the way from i to j and from i to k such that there exists at least   one lucky edge. A triplet (1, 2, 3) is different from (1, 3, 2) or (2, 1, 3). Also, all three nodes are pairwise distinct.\u00a0</p>\n<p>\nAn edge is considered lucky if has only 4 or 7 as its digits. For ex- 474 and 774 are lucky while 6, 87, 49 etc. are not lucky.\n</p>\n<p>\u00a0<br />\nHelp Raju in finding the total triplets of nodes.\n</p>\n<h3>Input</h3>\n<p>The first line contains the single integer n \u2014 the number of tree nodes</p>\n<p>Next n\u2009-\u20091 lines contain three integers each: u,v, w \u2014 the pair of nodes connected by the edge and the edge's weight</p>\n<h3>Output</h3>\n<p>One answer denoting the total number of triplets of nodes with one lucky edge.</p>\n<h3>Constraints</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><b>1</b> \u2264 <b>n</b> \u2264 <b>10<sup>4</sup></b></li>\n<li><b>1</b> \u2264 <b>u,v</b> \u2264 <b>N</b></li>\n<li><b>1</b> \u2264 <b>w</b> \u2264 <b>10<sup>9</sup></b></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Example</h3>\n<pre><b>Input:</b>\n4\n1 2 4\n3 1 2\n1 4 7\n\n\n<b>Output:</b>\n16</pre>",
